Document: binary_serialization_api
Path: godot/tutorials/io/binary_serialization_api.rst
Summary: This section describes the binary serialization format when `full_objects` is enabled, detailing how class names and properties are stored, and noting which properties are serialized based on usage flags.

`full_objects` enabled

*   Offset 4 (Length 4): Integer - Class name (String length).
*   Offset 8 (Length X): Bytes - Class name (UTF-8 encoded string).
*   Offset X+8 (Length 4): Integer - The number of properties that are serialized.

For each property:

*   Offset Y (Length 4): Integer - Property name (String length).
*   Offset Y+4 (Length Z): Bytes - Property name (UTF-8 encoded string).
*   Offset Y+4+Z (Length W): <variable> - Property value, using this same format.

Note: Not all properties are included. Only properties that are configured with the PROPERTY_USAGE_STORAGE flag set will be serialized. You can add a new usage flag to a property by overriding the _get_property_list method in your class. You can also check how property usage is configured by calling Object._get_property_list. See PropertyUsageFlags for the possible usage flags.
---CHUNK---
Document: Binary Serialization API
Path: godot/tutorials/io/binary_serialization_api.rst
Summary: This section describes the binary serialization format for a Dictionary.

Dictionary
- Offset: 4, Length: 4, Type: Integer. Description: `val&0x7FFFFFFF` equals elements, `val&0x80000000` equals shared (boolean).

Then what follows is, for amount of "elements", pairs of key and value, one after the other, using this same format.
---CHUNK---
Document: Binary Serialization API
Path: godot/tutorials/io/binary_serialization_api.rst
Summary: This section describes the binary serialization format for an Array.

An Array is serialized starting with a 4-byte Integer. The lower 31 bits of this integer (`val&0x7FFFFFFF`) represent the number of elements in the array. The most significant bit (`val&0x80000000`) indicates whether the array is shared (boolean). Then, for the amount of "elements", values are serialized one after the other, using this same format.
---CHUNK---
